# Azure App Service

## Definition

- Azure App Service is a fully managed Platform as a Service (PaaS) used to build, deploy, and host web applications, REST APIs, and mobile backends.
- Microsoft manages the underlying infrastructure, operating system, runtime, patching, and scaling.
- Developers only need to focus on writing and deploying application code.

---

## Why is it used?

- Host web applications.
- Deploy REST APIs.
- Reduce infrastructure management.
- Enable automatic scaling.
- Integrate with CI/CD pipelines.
- Improve application availability.

---

## Key Features

- Fully managed PaaS service.
- Supports .NET, Java, Node.js, Python, PHP, and Ruby.
- Built-in Auto Scaling.
- Deployment Slots.
- Custom Domains and SSL.
- Built-in Authentication.
- Continuous Deployment support.
- Backup and Restore.
- Monitoring with Azure Monitor and Application Insights.

---

## Advantages

- No server management.
- Fast application deployment.
- Built-in security.
- Automatic OS updates.
- Easy scaling.
- Supports DevOps integration.

---

## Disadvantages

- Less control over the operating system.
- Not suitable for applications requiring full server access.
- Pricing may increase for high-performance plans.

---

## Components

### App Service Plan

- Defines compute resources (CPU, Memory, Region, Pricing Tier).

### Web App

- Hosts websites and web applications.

### API App

- Hosts REST APIs.

### Deployment Slots

- Used for staging and production deployments.

### Custom Domain

- Maps your own domain to the application.

---

## Workflow

```text
Developer
     ↓
Push Application Code
     ↓
Azure App Service
     ↓
Build & Deploy
     ↓
Application Available
```

---

## Real-world Example

A company hosts its online shopping website on Azure App Service. Developers deploy new versions through GitHub Actions without managing virtual machines.

---

## Interview Tip

"Azure App Service is a PaaS offering where Microsoft manages the infrastructure while developers focus only on building and deploying applications."

---

## Quick Revision

- Fully managed PaaS.
- Hosts Web Apps and APIs.
- No server management.
- Supports multiple programming languages.
- Built-in scaling.
- Supports CI/CD.
- Uses App Service Plans.

